{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"35538fbc-a5c4-4d41-827e-5e275b239b81","content":"Here's what you need to change:\n\n### 1. Update NuGet packages\n- **Remove** `Microsoft.NET.Test.Sdk`\n- **Update** `NUnit3TestAdapter` to **v5.0.0+** (it bundles Microsoft.Testing.Platform support)\n- **Add** `Microsoft.Testing.Extensions.TrxReport` if you need TRX output\n\n### 2. Enable the new platform in your `.csproj`\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <EnableMSTestRunner>true</EnableMSTestRunner>\n  <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n> `EnableMSTestRunner` works for all frameworks that support Microsoft.Testing.Platform, not just MSTest.\n\n### 3. Run tests\n```bash\n# CLI (direct executable)\ndotnet run --project MyTests.csproj\n\n# Or via dotnet test (opt-in)\ndotnet test MyTests.csproj\n```\n\n### Key differences to be aware of\n- Your test project becomes an **executable** (`OutputType=Exe`).\n- CLI options change from `--filter` (VSTest) to `--filter` with a slightly different syntax; check `--help` on the built binary.\n- Extensions (code coverage, TRX reports) are added as NuGet packages instead of VSTest adapters.\n\nThat's the core migration. NUnit's own test framework package (`NUnit` 3.x/4.x) stays unchanged.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e4c89b8e-a193-469e-a6dd-e1c310872583","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about migrating their NUnit test project from VSTest to Microsoft.Testing.Platform. This is a knowledge question - I can answer it directly without needing to explore any codebase.\n\nLet me provide a concise answer about the migration steps.","outputTokens":421,"requestId":"E3DB:14659B:16615AC:18F640F:6A051F51"},"id":"52e8d146-af6c-465e-8efb-2296142f6d71","timestamp":"2026-05-14T01:03:24.800Z","parentId":"65994cbe-1bb1-4deb-b1e9-2a4d3503cd80"}
